{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510938"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:35:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11661"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11661"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.05,0.3,0.23,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113191"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4282"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45985"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113191"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one day history of increasing central abdominal pain and abdominal distension. This is accompanied with constipation for the past three days. His medical history includes a sigmoid colectomy for carcinoma eight years previously. On examination he looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 100/86 mmHg, pulse 104/min and temperature 37.2C. His abdomen is distended and soft. There is localised tenderness and guarding on the right side. A plain abdominal X-ray is arranged (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT abdomen","Rectal flatus tube","Colonoscopic decompression","Nasogastric decompression","Laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of large bowel obstruction most likely as a result of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E. The presentation of acute colicky abdominal pain accompanied with abdominal distension should always raise suspicion of intestinal obstruction. In this case, his history of previous abdominal surgery further increases his risks. The examination findings of tachycardia, relative hypotension and localised peritonitis raise the possibility of intestinal ischaemia as a result of mechanical obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a massively dilated loop of large bowel which is focused on the right side, confirming the diagnosis of caecal volvulus. Furthermore, he has signs of localised peritonitis in the region consistent with the likely site of the apex of the volvulus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires rapid surgical intervention to reduce the risk of progression of intestinal ischaemia to infarction. A\u003Cstrong\u003E laparotomy \u003C/strong\u003Eis the correct management option. It is most likely that the volvulus has now developed an ischaemic element and must be decompressed. The viability of the bowel needs to be assessed and this can only be done by surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst\u003Cstrong\u003E CT scanning of the abdomen \u003C/strong\u003Eis an integral component of the assessment of the acute abdomen in many situations, in these circumstances it is very unlikely to yield any further information which would influence the management plan of prompt surgical exploration. It might also delay the planned surgery. Whilst less important in the older patient, it must always be remembered that CT imaging exposes the patient to considerable radiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectal flatus tube \u003C/strong\u003Eis not an appropriate management plan for caecal volvulus with signs of bowel ischaemia. Rectal flatus tube might be done alongside flexible sigmoidoscope in patients with suspected sigmoid volvulus without any signs of complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopic decompression \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the recommended treatment for mechanical large bowel obstruction. Colonoscopy increase the risk of bowel perforation and may lead to further complications in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENasogastric decompression \u003C/strong\u003Eis a useful initial resuscitation plan for haemodynamically stable patients presenting with bowel obstruction. However in this case as the patient has signs of developing bowel ischaemia, urgent laparotomy is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Characteristic findings of caecal volvulus on plain film include massively dilated loop of large bowel which is focused on the right side."],"references":["Lou Z, Yu ED, Zhang W, Meng RG, Hao LQ, Fu CG. Appropriate treatment of acute sigmoid volvulus in the emergency setting. World Journal of Gastroenterology: WJG. 2013 Aug 8;19(30):4979.","Habre J, Sautot-Vial N, Marcotte C, Benchimol D. Caecal volvulus. The American Journal of Surgery. 2008 Nov 1;196(5):e48-9.","Panteleimonitis S, Nash G. Gastroscope guidewire volvulus tube decompression. Techniques in Coloproctology. 2019 Feb 4;23(4):385-6."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11661"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"medi